{
  "text": "The Intel 432 is notable as an \"object-oriented\" or \"object-based\"l architecture. Just as the Smalltalk language [CITATION_1] encapsulates all data into objects that can be manipulated in carefully constrained ways, the 432 imposes similar restrictions on all online storage: -All information is encapsulated into protected sets called objects (instruction segments, data structures, processes, messages). -Every memory reference, whether an instruction fetch or operand access, is checked for read/write privilege and base/bounds validity. -Pointers to objects are protected. These pointers are not directly manipulated by the user program, but only by trusted hardware and microcode on behalf of the user.",
  "citation_candidates": [
